into those shoes, cautiously,

00:11:49.556 --> 00:11:50.930
of course, because
you never know

00:11:50.930 --> 00:11:52.880
how someone's going to react.

00:11:52.880 --> 00:11:57.770
But if you go into
that truth, again,

00:11:57.770 --> 00:12:01.790
with empathy and with
humility-- my god--

00:12:01.790 --> 00:12:05.030
then I think the door can
open to so much possibility.

00:12:05.030 --> 00:12:06.810
And that's what it's all about--

00:12:06.810 --> 00:12:07.310
possibility.

00:12:07.310 --> 00:12:08.809
CHALMERS BROWNE:
Is there an example

00:12:08.809 --> 00:12:12.019
that you can think of,
where telling that truth--

00:12:12.019 --> 00:12:13.685
CLAUDE SILVER: Yeah,
there's an example.

00:12:13.685 --> 00:12:15.050
I mean, when did I get here?

00:12:15.050 --> 00:12:19.370
So I think an hour
ago, I was in a room

00:12:19.370 --> 00:12:23.930
with a very senior
account holder, account--

00:12:23.930 --> 00:12:26.080
our client service person.

00:12:26.080 --> 00:12:30.650
And this person was telling
me that he has been exploring

00:12:30.650 --> 00:12:32.210
his team for the
last three months,

00:12:32.210 --> 00:12:33.835
and these are the
three buckets that he

00:12:33.835 --> 00:12:36.890
thinks are wrong with his team.

00:12:36.890 --> 00:12:38.360
So he's probably my age.

00:12:38.360 --> 00:12:42.091
He's in his 40s, and maybe
he knows more about life

00:12:42.091 --> 00:12:42.590
than I do.

00:12:42.590 --> 00:12:43.500
I have no idea.

00:12:43.500 --> 00:12:47.305
But he and I have had many
conversations over the past,

00:12:47.305 --> 00:12:48.680
I would say, eight
or nine months

00:12:48.680 --> 00:12:52.400
about these issues in his
team, and only today, he's

00:12:52.400 --> 00:12:54.020
bringing them to me.

00:12:54.020 --> 00:12:56.720
So what I did say to him
is, with all due respect,

00:12:56.720 --> 00:12:58.970
I really believe that
you've been protecting

00:12:58.970 --> 00:13:01.400
your team this entire time.

00:13:01.400 --> 00:13:03.710
There's no need to
protect your team,

00:13:03.710 --> 00:13:05.510
and these three
buckets that you just

00:13:05.510 --> 00:13:08.360
shared with us should have been
shared with me nine months ago,

00:13:08.360 --> 00:13:10.250
because we could have fixed it.

00:13:10.250 --> 00:13:12.620
We didn't need to go through
all the rigmarole and all

00:13:12.620 --> 00:13:16.484
the people issues and all the
hardship and all the missed

00:13:16.484 --> 00:13:17.900
deadlines and all
of those things,

00:13:17.900 --> 00:13:21.410
if we just could get truth.

00:13:21.410 --> 00:13:24.470
So that's probably the
most recent conversation,

00:13:24.470 --> 00:13:26.690
and he took it as
well as can be.

00:13:26.690 --> 00:13:29.790
We'll see what happens
when I get back to work.

00:13:29.790 --> 00:13:34.400
But again, you go into
it with as much grace

00:13:34.400 --> 00:13:37.880
and just generosity.

00:13:37.880 --> 00:13:40.346
I want to help him.

00:13:40.346 --> 00:13:41.720
CHALMERS BROWNE:
So your role was

00:13:41.720 --> 00:13:45.080
created to help preserve
Vayner's culture,

00:13:45.080 --> 00:13:46.820
while it grows rapidly.

00:13:46.820 --> 00:13:48.980
We know a little bit
about that here at Google.

00:13:52.910 --> 00:13:54.890
What are the elements
of Vayner's culture

00:13:54.890 --> 00:13:59.790
that you most fear losing as you
continue to expand and scale?

00:13:59.790 --> 00:14:02.540
CLAUDE SILVER: Yeah,
so yeah, this role

00:14:02.540 --> 00:14:03.890
was created to scale Gary.

00:14:03.890 --> 00:14:06.110
And he says to scale the
unscalable, which I think

00:14:06.110 --> 00:14:07.740
is a phenomenal way to say it.

00:14:07.740 --> 00:14:09.721
I mean, how do we scale culture?

00:14:09.721 --> 00:14:10.720
That's the big question.

00:14:10.720 --> 00:14:12.761
It's a question I get all
the time and a question

00:14:12.761 --> 00:14:15.830
I'm sure you guys get at almost
80,000 people and wanting

00:14:15.830 --> 00:14:20.220
to maintain Google
across the world.

00:14:20.220 --> 00:14:23.780
So our culture is really built
on a few different values

00:14:23.780 --> 00:14:26.300
that I can say, over the
last eight and 1/2 years,

00:14:26.300 --> 00:14:29.300
are pretty tried and true.

00:14:29.300 --> 00:14:33.440
Empathy, which I will
call heart, speed,

00:14:33.440 --> 00:14:39.480
which I would call hustle,
hustle and heart, possibility--

00:14:39.480 --> 00:14:42.870
we work for an entrepreneur, and
everything really is possible.

00:14:42.870 --> 00:14:45.290
There is a yes all the
time, until there isn't.

00:14:45.290 --> 00:14:49.860
But it takes a very long time
to get to the no, if ever.

00:14:49.860 --> 00:14:54.420
Positivity-- I mean Gary
overindexes as an optimist.

00:14:54.420 --> 00:14:57.500
I'm probably very
close behind him.

00:14:57.500 --> 00:15:01.520
And winning,
competitiveness-- and those

00:15:01.520 --> 00:15:04.790
are things I believe
are still in our DNA,

00:15:04.790 --> 00:15:06.520
absolutely, over
eight and 1/2 years.

00:15:06.520 --> 00:15:08.900
But those are things
that we need to continue

00:15:08.900 --> 00:15:10.700
to stoke the fire on.

00:15:10.700 --> 00:15:13.940
So for example, let's take the
conversation that I just had.

00:15:13.940 --> 00:15:15.980
That conversation
was out of line

00:15:15.980 --> 00:15:18.020
and out of touch
with our culture,

00:15:18.020 --> 00:15:21.270
because the winning
was misguided.

00:15:21.270 --> 00:15:25.820
The wanting to win
was cased in fear.

00:15:25.820 --> 00:15:27.260
That's not one of our values.

00:15:27.260 --> 00:15:33.350
It's not how we use
and foster our culture.

00:15:33.350 --> 00:15:35.210
And that's just talking
to one individual.

00:15:35.210 --> 00:15:37.340
Where is that-- is
that spread anywhere?

00:15:37.340 --> 00:15:40.304
I mean, so the most
important thing

00:15:40.304 --> 00:15:41.720
that I'm doing
every single day is

00:15:41.720 --> 00:15:43.170
I'm talking to a lot of people.

00:15:43.170 --> 00:15:45.170
Quite frankly, I'm listening
to a lot of people,

00:15:45.170 --> 00:15:48.440
and I'm just collecting
data, collecting information,

00:15:48.440 --> 00:15:52.700
I'm holding space to see what
happens, to see what comes out.

00:15:52.700 --> 00:15:56.390
And as I'm speaking to
people and collecting data,

00:15:56.390 --> 00:15:58.010
I'm looking for patterns.

00:15:58.010 --> 00:16:00.800
And I'm looking to hear if
I hear a similarity on one

00:16:00.800 --> 00:16:04.162
certain team or if I hear a
similarity on a department,

00:16:04.162 --> 00:16:06.620
even though the department
might be in a different country.

00:16:06.620 --> 00:16:08.540
It might have legs in
a different culture--

00:16:08.540 --> 00:16:11.900
different company--
sorry, different country.

00:16:11.900 --> 00:16:13.790
And so as I hear
these patterns, that's

00:16:13.790 --> 00:16:17.690
where we start to deploy
more people that are what I

00:16:17.690 --> 00:16:19.520
like to call culture carriers.

00:16:19.520 --> 00:16:21.420
By no means is their
title culture carrier,

00:16:21.420 --> 00:16:24.110
although they should put
it in their signature.

00:16:24.110 --> 00:16:27.989
These are people that really
get a sense of the water

00:16:27.989 --> 00:16:29.530
that we're drinking
every single day.

00:16:29.530 --> 00:16:30.350
It's not Kool-Aid.

00:16:30.350 --> 00:16:31.220
It's water.

00:16:31.220 --> 00:16:32.030
It's pure.

00:16:32.030 --> 00:16:34.430
It's real.

00:16:34.430 --> 00:16:37.820
And so in every office, and
certainly in our offices here

00:16:37.820 --> 00:16:40.370
in New York, which
we have two, I

00:16:40.370 --> 00:16:45.950
can depend on and rely
on using and asking

00:16:45.950 --> 00:16:47.780
that person or that
person or that person

00:16:47.780 --> 00:16:51.920
to go take that person for a
walk or for a cup of coffee,

00:16:51.920 --> 00:16:54.680
or go have a little mini town
hall with those eight people,

00:16:54.680 --> 00:16:57.200
who are just kind of crusty.

00:16:57.200 --> 00:16:59.290
So that is something that is--

00:16:59.290 --> 00:17:01.220
it's like a 24/7 job.

00:17:01.220 --> 00:17:05.990
It's an absolute 24/7 job, which
meeting with people one on one,

00:17:05.990 --> 00:17:08.060
having hangouts with
people, going to--

00:17:08.060 --> 00:17:10.640
I'll start a big
round of office visits

00:17:10.640 --> 00:17:13.901
next week in different
countries and different cities.

00:17:13.901 --> 00:17:15.859
And so making sure that
we have that high touch

00:17:15.859 --> 00:17:16.817
at every single moment.

00:17:16.817 --> 00:17:19.606
Obviously, Gary is doing
the same exact thing.

00:17:19.606 --> 00:17:21.230
He might be doing
five-minute meetings.

00:17:21.230 --> 00:17:23.329
He might be doing
a lot of texting,

00:17:23.329 --> 00:17:29.300
but we try to cover as much
ground as we possibly can,

00:17:29.300 --> 00:17:33.560
and ensuring that the
culture is still being fed

00:17:33.560 --> 00:17:39.385
and watered so that we can have
new sprouts every single day.

00:17:39.385 --> 00:17:41.894
I talk in metaphors
a lot, but that's

00:17:41.894 --> 00:17:43.560
what it looks like
to me, quite frankly.

00:17:43.560 --> 00:17:45.120
It's 800 people now--

00:17:45.120 --> 00:17:45.620
what?

00:17:45.620 --> 00:17:49.447
I think 805 people, I
think, and that's a lot.

00:17:49.447 --> 00:17:50.780
That's just a lot of heartbeats.

00:17:50.780 --> 00:17:53.300
It's a lot of mouths to
feed, and certainly don't

00:17:53.300 --> 00:17:57.072
need to explain that to Google.

00:17:57.072 --> 00:17:59.030
So we've got we've got
a lot of learning to do,

00:17:59.030 --> 00:18:02.690
but I do think that we've
implemented some really good

00:18:02.690 --> 00:18:06.980
tried and tested abilities now.

00:18:06.980 --> 00:18:08.600
CHALMERS BROWNE: In
the run-up to 800,

00:18:08.600 --> 00:18:11.360
are there things that
you feel like you sort

00:18:11.360 --> 00:18:14.720
of lost irretrievably
or things that

00:18:14.720 --> 00:18:20.150
just couldn't survive from the
smaller scale to the larger

00:18:20.150 --> 00:18:20.741
scale?

00:18:20.741 --> 00:18:22.490
CLAUDE SILVER: I don't
think we lost them.

00:18:22.490 --> 00:18:25.500
I think we lost sight of
them, and then got them back.

00:18:25.500 --> 00:18:26.600
That's what I think.

00:18:26.600 --> 00:18:29.260
So in terms of growing,
growing, growing,

00:18:29.260 --> 00:18:32.180
that's just-- for example,
the talent team that's here.

00:18:32.180 --> 00:18:34.650
I mean, there was
a period of time,

00:18:34.650 --> 00:18:36.260
and there's only
about five of them

00:18:36.260 --> 00:18:37.590
in all different countries.

00:18:37.590 --> 00:18:41.364
In New York, we've got
three, three or four.

00:18:41.364 --> 00:18:43.780
But there was a time that they
were hiring hand over fist.

00:18:43.780 --> 00:18:47.630
I mean we couldn't bring
enough bodies into the offices

00:18:47.630 --> 00:18:48.740
and into our world.

00:18:48.740 --> 00:18:52.300
And what we lost
sight of was training,

00:18:52.300 --> 00:18:55.070
and what we lost sight
of was the orientation.

00:18:55.070 --> 00:18:58.910
And what we ended up doing
is throwing them into a fire

00:18:58.910 --> 00:19:00.830
without giving them
a sense of what's

00:19:00.830 --> 00:19:05.780
in our DNA, what's in our
bloodstream and our water.

00:19:05.780 --> 00:19:09.960
And there were moments, I would
say, in the last 18 months,

00:19:09.960 --> 00:19:14.150
two years that you
could feel the ground

00:19:14.150 --> 00:19:18.262
start to not tremble, but just
start to shake a little bit,

00:19:18.262 --> 00:19:20.720
or the wheels on the bus just
start to rattle a little bit,

00:19:20.720 --> 00:19:22.460
a little harder than I like.

00:19:22.460 --> 00:19:26.180
I like a lot of speed,
but it was a little much.

00:19:26.180 --> 00:19:28.250
And in those moments,
that's something

00:19:28.250 --> 00:19:31.040
that I talked to Gary about, I'm
going to talk to my team about,

00:19:31.040 --> 00:19:33.690
and we have to kind of do a
full court press in that moment.

00:19:33.690 --> 00:19:35.106
There's some things
that we're not

00:19:35.106 --> 00:19:38.430
going to be able to retrofit
and change, but going forward,

00:19:38.430 --> 00:19:40.880
we know how important
it is to orient.

00:19:40.880 --> 00:19:43.790
We have a week-long
orientation--

00:19:43.790 --> 00:19:47.450
and how important it is for
that employee to really,

00:19:47.450 --> 00:19:51.630
really connect to get a sense
of belonging, tried and true.

00:19:51.630 --> 00:19:53.300
We want them here.

00:19:53.300 --> 00:19:56.000
We've gone through three rounds
of interviewing, maybe four.

00:19:56.000 --> 00:19:57.830
And so when they
come in, we already

00:19:57.830 --> 00:20:00.531
have this incredible
sense of belief in them,

00:20:00.531 --> 00:20:02.030
and it takes an
employee, obviously,

00:20:02.030 --> 00:20:04.730
a longer time to
believe in the org.

00:20:04.730 --> 00:20:08.130
But in those cases, where
we got lost a little bit.

00:20:08.130 --> 00:20:10.209
And so anyway,
we've retrofitted.

00:20:10.209 --> 00:20:11.750
CHALMERS BROWNE:
And are there things

00:20:11.750 --> 00:20:15.110
that you find that you can
do at scale that you couldn't

00:20:15.110 --> 00:20:17.240
do when you were smaller?

00:20:17.240 --> 00:20:18.950
CLAUDE SILVER: That,
I actually believe

00:20:18.950 --> 00:20:22.109
in terms of going back
in time a little bit.

00:20:22.109 --> 00:20:23.900
Back in time's not the
right way to say it,

00:20:23.900 --> 00:20:25.310
because we can't
go back in time.

00:20:25.310 --> 00:20:28.640
But we can certainly go back
and have that conversation

00:20:28.640 --> 00:20:33.020
with that swath of people
that we may have missed.

00:20:33.020 --> 00:20:35.840
We moved to-- we opened up
our first international office

00:20:35.840 --> 00:20:38.930
about 15 months ago in
London, and in doing so,

00:20:38.930 --> 00:20:42.860
we sent out ex-pats
to open up the office.

00:20:42.860 --> 00:20:45.500
One of the things we
learned very quickly is--

00:20:45.500 --> 00:20:49.030
and I worked in London for a
significant amount of time.

00:20:49.030 --> 00:20:51.740
So it's something I
knew, but as an ex-pat,

00:20:51.740 --> 00:20:54.200
it's different with
different glasses on.

00:20:54.200 --> 00:20:56.780
It's so important to get
locals in your office

00:20:56.780 --> 00:20:59.540
and get locals in
your office fast.

00:20:59.540 --> 00:21:03.700
Otherwise, it really is like the
American invasion in many ways,

00:21:03.700 --> 00:21:05.127
and that's not going to work.

00:21:05.127 --> 00:21:06.960
That's not going to
work in another country,

00:21:06.960 --> 00:21:09.650
but it's certainly not going
to work when you are a local,

00:21:09.650 --> 00:21:12.080
and you walk in, and
there's eight ex-pats,

00:21:12.080 --> 00:21:14.100
and they're telling
you what to do.

00:21:14.100 --> 00:21:18.110
So those are things that we've
had to look at and reverse

00:21:18.110 --> 00:21:19.850
engineer as we go forward.

00:21:23.430 --> 00:21:25.340
CHALMERS BROWNE: So
we're just finishing up

00:21:25.340 --> 00:21:28.860
our performance management
and compensation cycle.

00:21:28.860 --> 00:21:31.440
Every company has them
in some form or another.

00:21:31.440 --> 00:21:33.470
But those processes--
performance management,

00:21:33.470 --> 00:21:35.660
compensation planning--

00:21:35.660 --> 00:21:39.680
they're often seen as sort
of being directly at odds

00:21:39.680 --> 00:21:44.090
with the effort to create
psychological safety, a culture

00:21:44.090 --> 00:21:45.050
of trust.

00:21:45.050 --> 00:21:48.560
How do you handle performance
evaluation and rewards

00:21:48.560 --> 00:21:51.852
without undermining
the honey empire?

00:21:51.852 --> 00:21:53.060
CLAUDE SILVER: It's so tough.

00:21:53.060 --> 00:21:57.770
I mean this crew in front
of me that's on my team--

00:21:57.770 --> 00:22:00.140
they're the ones that take a
little bit of the bruising,

00:22:00.140 --> 00:22:03.710
because there is such a
juxtaposition between we

00:22:03.710 --> 00:22:04.230
love you.

00:22:04.230 --> 00:22:05.540
We believe in you, We want you.

00:22:05.540 --> 00:22:06.350
You have a home.

00:22:06.350 --> 00:22:07.570
We want you here forever.

00:22:07.570 --> 00:22:09.710
Here's 6%.

00:22:09.710 --> 00:22:14.390
Or you just got all fives on
a review, on a review form,

00:22:14.390 --> 00:22:17.770
because we just got out
of our cycle as well.

00:22:17.770 --> 00:22:22.940
But you're not getting
promoted, but here's 10%.

00:22:22.940 --> 00:22:24.600
These are really
hard conversations.

00:22:24.600 --> 00:22:28.400
I don't have the answer,
other than so much high touch.

00:22:28.400 --> 00:22:31.580
And that means spending
time with that employee,

00:22:31.580 --> 00:22:33.260
going back to that
employee, letting

00:22:33.260 --> 00:22:36.080
them know we work for them,
working with their manager,

00:22:36.080 --> 00:22:37.590
seeing how we can--

00:22:37.590 --> 00:22:42.920
if we're not able to give
them the salary increase

00:22:42.920 --> 00:22:45.440
that they were so hoping
for, and it is 6%,

00:22:45.440 --> 00:22:48.289
or it is 8%, making sure that
what's in their review in terms

00:22:48.289 --> 00:22:50.330
of their training and
development or their growth

00:22:50.330 --> 00:22:52.850
plans, we are hitting
immediately or as soon

00:22:52.850 --> 00:22:54.370
as we possibly can.

00:22:54.370 --> 00:22:56.300
That's one way I think
that we can surround

00:22:56.300 --> 00:23:00.920
that person or that
cohort with as much heart,

00:23:00.920 --> 00:23:03.050
as much honey as
we possibly can.

00:23:03.050 --> 00:23:05.630
Spending time with Gary is
always going to be a benefit,

00:23:05.630 --> 00:23:08.250
and it's weird to kind of
dangle that in front sometimes.

00:23:08.250 --> 00:23:11.840
But it is so
incredibly helpful when

00:23:11.840 --> 00:23:18.470
you get that time with Gary, and
he's able to, in his own words,

00:23:18.470 --> 00:23:21.020
really, really hone
you into the vision,

00:23:21.020 --> 00:23:24.189
because the vision is--
the vision's amazing.

00:23:24.189 --> 00:23:25.730
The vision of what
we're doing, we're

00:23:25.730 --> 00:23:28.730
building an agency so that
at some point in time,

00:23:28.730 --> 00:23:32.930
we can buy brands and own
them and create the marketing

00:23:32.930 --> 00:23:34.430
and awareness for them--

00:23:34.430 --> 00:23:35.600
that's awesome.

00:23:35.600 --> 00:23:38.740
There's not a lot of
agencies that are doing that.

00:23:38.740 --> 00:23:43.490
But it is something we need
to spend a lot of time with

00:23:43.490 --> 00:23:47.370
and a lot of not coddling and
not pampering, but just, again,

00:23:47.370 --> 00:23:47.870
high touch.

00:23:47.870 --> 00:23:50.420
I say that phrase a
lot, but it is really

00:23:50.420 --> 00:23:57.300
what we do, from a
resident on up to an SVP.

00:23:57.300 --> 00:24:01.130
CHALMERS BROWNE: And sort of in
line with that, as Chief Heart

00:24:01.130 --> 00:24:05.420
officer, how do you go about
helping someone when they're

00:24:05.420 --> 00:24:07.240
not succeeding in their role?

00:24:07.240 --> 00:24:09.740
CLAUDE SILVER: So when they're
