00:48:18.210 --> 00:48:24.090
So thank you for the question,
and I'm open to any ideas

00:48:24.090 --> 00:48:27.170
to chomp on for
how we solve this.

00:48:27.170 --> 00:48:29.742
Yeah, thank you.

00:48:29.742 --> 00:48:32.150
You can tell I'm
passionate about that.

00:48:32.150 --> 00:48:34.290
Come on.

00:48:34.290 --> 00:48:38.520
CHALMERS BROWNE: So if
you're successful in making

00:48:38.520 --> 00:48:41.760
your workplace a place
where people feel included,

00:48:41.760 --> 00:48:45.820
feel at home, what's your
approach to work-life balance?

00:48:45.820 --> 00:48:47.950
How do you make sure that--

00:48:47.950 --> 00:48:50.010
is there a danger of
tipping that too far,

00:48:50.010 --> 00:48:54.120
where some people might fail
to build or maintain their life

00:48:54.120 --> 00:48:55.930
outside of work?

00:48:55.930 --> 00:48:58.740
CLAUDE SILVER: So the
sarcastic me says to you,

00:48:58.740 --> 00:49:01.380
is there such a thing
as work-life balance?

00:49:01.380 --> 00:49:04.250
I mean, sarcastic
and slightly true.

00:49:04.250 --> 00:49:06.060
What I do is--

00:49:06.060 --> 00:49:11.680
by no means is it 24/7, but
I'm working quite a bit.

00:49:11.680 --> 00:49:15.630
And I'm OK with that,
because I've chosen this job.

00:49:15.630 --> 00:49:19.110
I've actually turned
over this idea

00:49:19.110 --> 00:49:20.850
of work-life balance
for the moment,

00:49:20.850 --> 00:49:22.719
and I look at energy management.

00:49:22.719 --> 00:49:24.510
And that's kind of the
term that I look at,

00:49:24.510 --> 00:49:29.620
and I try to share a lot
more of with our employees.

00:49:29.620 --> 00:49:33.510
We have 80% millennials, so
that right there in itself is--

00:49:33.510 --> 00:49:34.560
and we're an agency.

00:49:34.560 --> 00:49:36.670
So that is as
cutthroat as it gets.

00:49:36.670 --> 00:49:40.189
I mean, you are
beholden to a client,

00:49:40.189 --> 00:49:41.730
and that means you've
got to get that

00:49:41.730 --> 00:49:43.771
out when you said you were
going to get that out,

00:49:43.771 --> 00:49:45.600
unless you're going
to answer the phone

00:49:45.600 --> 00:49:47.730
tomorrow with a
client breathing down

00:49:47.730 --> 00:49:49.890
your neck, which happens also.

00:49:49.890 --> 00:49:52.740
But this idea of
energy management

00:49:52.740 --> 00:49:55.620
is something that makes
more sense to me today,

00:49:55.620 --> 00:49:59.940
rather than work-life balance,
unfortunately, or fortunately.

00:49:59.940 --> 00:50:02.730
Energy management is
really being aware

00:50:02.730 --> 00:50:07.850
of how you're feeling,
where your anxiety level is.

00:50:07.850 --> 00:50:08.790
Are you at Code Red?

00:50:08.790 --> 00:50:10.165
Because if you're
at Code Red, we

00:50:10.165 --> 00:50:12.360
need to figure out
how to get to pink

00:50:12.360 --> 00:50:15.030
or how to get to an orange.

00:50:15.030 --> 00:50:18.810
Setting up little milestones
across your day to,

00:50:18.810 --> 00:50:21.621
then, celebrate, take
a break, so you're

00:50:21.621 --> 00:50:22.870
going to work for 10 minutes--

00:50:22.870 --> 00:50:25.590
I'm sorry-- you're going to
work for two hours on this one

00:50:25.590 --> 00:50:27.756
project that you're working
on, this one spreadsheet

00:50:27.756 --> 00:50:29.610
or this one deliverable.

00:50:29.610 --> 00:50:32.805
You're going to get to a
stopping point, where you know

00:50:32.805 --> 00:50:35.400
you can get up, take a breath,
and you can go check Instagram

00:50:35.400 --> 00:50:36.067
for 10 minutes.

00:50:36.067 --> 00:50:37.650
You can go out and
walk the High Line.

00:50:37.650 --> 00:50:38.941
You can go for a cup of coffee.

00:50:38.941 --> 00:50:40.179
You can go out to lunch.

00:50:40.179 --> 00:50:42.720
Those are things, I think going
back to my project management

00:50:42.720 --> 00:50:44.553
roots, I think are
really, really important.

00:50:44.553 --> 00:50:48.170
I think if I'm looking at
a Gantt chart of my day

00:50:48.170 --> 00:50:50.010
and where my energy
tips and falls

00:50:50.010 --> 00:50:52.170
and after lunch and
whatnot, just being super,

00:50:52.170 --> 00:50:57.420
super aware of how
I'm feeling inside

00:50:57.420 --> 00:51:00.000
and how an employee
is feeling inside

00:51:00.000 --> 00:51:01.950
and how that's
manifesting, whether or not

00:51:01.950 --> 00:51:04.980
that's manifesting physically,
and maybe someone's grinding

00:51:04.980 --> 00:51:07.050
their teeth or
getting really upset,

00:51:07.050 --> 00:51:10.350
or how that's just
manifesting inside

00:51:10.350 --> 00:51:13.620
with not feeling good
enough about yourself

00:51:13.620 --> 00:51:15.962
and feeling
extremely competitive

00:51:15.962 --> 00:51:16.920
with that other person.

00:51:16.920 --> 00:51:19.320
Or gosh, you heard that
person's getting 10k more,

00:51:19.320 --> 00:51:21.360
and you're doing the same job.

00:51:21.360 --> 00:51:26.880
So managing one's energy is
super important right now.

00:51:26.880 --> 00:51:30.910
Yes, having work-life
balance is like a dream.

00:51:30.910 --> 00:51:33.450
I think that if any of us
can go back in time and clock

00:51:33.450 --> 00:51:36.030
in and clock out, as
some of our parents dead,

00:51:36.030 --> 00:51:39.000
or work that eight-hour day
with a half an hour lunch

00:51:39.000 --> 00:51:41.700
break, as some
people do in Europe,

00:51:41.700 --> 00:51:46.800
quite frankly, that
is kind of utopic.

00:51:46.800 --> 00:51:49.230
And there are places to do that.

00:51:49.230 --> 00:51:50.820
I can't tell you
that agency life

00:51:50.820 --> 00:51:54.120
is that place right
now, and maybe

00:51:54.120 --> 00:51:56.880
as we see more remote working--

00:51:56.880 --> 00:51:57.980
you do that really well.

00:51:57.980 --> 00:52:01.187
I mean Google does
extremely well.

00:52:01.187 --> 00:52:03.270
But agencies are funny,
because for the most part,

00:52:03.270 --> 00:52:07.830
you're in roles that you need
to be present on a floor for.

00:52:07.830 --> 00:52:11.230
You need to be able to look
across that desk and say, hey,

00:52:11.230 --> 00:52:13.080
will you look at my
deck for a second?

00:52:13.080 --> 00:52:15.570
There's such a collaborative
yin and yang there.

00:52:15.570 --> 00:52:22.840
So work-life balance is
something that I'm aware of,

00:52:22.840 --> 00:52:25.920
I wish I had that answer
to, but time management

00:52:25.920 --> 00:52:28.800
is where I'm really
trying to get more people

00:52:28.800 --> 00:52:31.560
to focus on, and be
aware of just how they're

00:52:31.560 --> 00:52:33.300
feeling in any given
moment and when

00:52:33.300 --> 00:52:35.100
they can just take a time out.

00:52:35.100 --> 00:52:37.390
Timeouts really,
really, really help,

00:52:37.390 --> 00:52:39.390
and we all deserve timeouts.

00:52:39.390 --> 00:52:43.112
Like, what are we doing here?

00:52:43.112 --> 00:52:44.070
CHALMERS BROWNE: Great.

00:52:44.070 --> 00:52:45.360
Well, thank you so
much for coming.

00:52:45.360 --> 00:52:46.020
CLAUDE SILVER:
Thank you very much.

00:52:46.020 --> 00:52:46.530
CHALMERS BROWNE: We're at time.

00:52:46.530 --> 00:52:48.024
Let's have a hand for Claude.

00:52:48.024 --> 00:52:48.940
CLAUDE SILVER: Thanks.

00:52:48.940 --> 00:52:52.890
[APPLAUSE]

